03804nam a22005175i 9780804773379DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222009cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047733797 a10.1515/97808047733792doi  a(DE-B1597)581315  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDG445b.B57 2010 7aHIS0200002bisacsh04a709.2/2452221 aBiow, Douglas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Your Face :bProfessional Improprieties and the Art of Being Conspicuous in Sixteenth-Century Italy /cDouglas Biow. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b20 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tNote on Translations -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Diplomacy -- t1. Baldassar Castiglione and the Art of Being Inconspicuously Conspicuous -- tPart Two. Food -- t2. Pietro Aretino and the Art of Conspicuous Consumption -- t3. Michelangelo Buonarroti and the Art of Conspicuous Absorption -- tPart Three. Objects -- t4. Benvenuto Cellini and the Art of Conspicuous Production -- t5. Anton Francesco Doni and the Art of Conspicuous Reproduction -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix: Extant Manuscripts with Designs by Doni, in Rough Order -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Your Face concentrates on the Renaissance concern with "self-fashioning" by examining how a group of Renaissance artists and writers encoded their own improprieties in their works of art. In the elitist court society of sixteenth-century Italy, where moderation, limitation, and discretion were generally held to be essential virtues, these men consistently sought to stand out and to underplay their conspicuousness at once. The heroes (or anti-heroes) of this book—Michelangelo Buonarroti, Benvenuto Cellini, Pietro Aretino, and Anton Francesco Doni—violated norms of decorum by promoting themselves aggressively and by using writing or artworks to memorialize their assertiveness and intractable delight in parading themselves as transgressive and insubordinate on a grand scale. Focusing on these sorts of writers and visual artists, Biow constructs a version of the Italian Renaissance that is neither the elegant one of Castiglione's and Vasari's courts—so recently favored in scholarly accounts—nor the dark, conspiratorial one of Niccolò Machiavelli's and Francesco Guicciardini's princely states.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aArtistszItalyxHistoryy16th century. 0aAuthors, Italiany16th century. 0aEccentrics and eccentricitieszItalyxHistoryy16th century. 0aPersonality and creative abilityzItalyxHistoryy16th century. 4aArt. 4aHistory -- Intellectual and Cultural. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804773379zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804773379423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804773379/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles